♿ ⭐ PSA ⭐♿
Yesterday was a rough day. 🥴🫠 #continuetoprayforTHISSPECIFICsaint - I'm sharing this as a teachable moment. If you have enjoyed any of my content, please listen up. As much as humanly possible ⭐⭐ DO NOT BLOCK WHEELCHAIR RAMPS EVEN IF FOR A MOMENT. ⭐⭐ I realized that things come up, but every parking space except my car was EMPTY AND AVAILABLE, and this person CHOSE to pull up and block the ramp. 🙃 Their car is empty, and they are nowhere to be found. I know you think "I'm just running in for a sec," but that meant had to pick up my son (57 lbs) and his wheelchair (19 lbs) to get him off the curb or walk all the way to the other ramp waaaaaaaaay down the sidewalk and then come waaaaaaaaay back up to my car. 😐 And that's *IF* there is another ramp at all. All because you didn't feel like pulling into available parking spaces. 😐 It didn't help that the reason I had him is that we were on the way to the doctor yet again. You would be shocked at how often this happens to me (unless you are a wheelchair user then you already know the deal). If I will ever influence you in any way, shape, or form, this is it. ‼️‼️‼️

SO ... 

... if this here Glamazini has ever made you laugh, chuckle, think, or helped you in any way please think of this picture when you are deciding to park your vehicle. And know that someone like me is grateful for your intentional choice to be a better human EVEN IF YOU NEVER SEE THEM. 😐

Oh & ⭐⭐ SHARE THIS ON YOUR STORY PLEASE ⭐⭐ let the world know. Thank you very much. 🫶🏾

Oh and please do not take it upon yourself to police others' behaviors around accessible spaces and ramps. This is about YOU making better choices amen. Amen.

Be well, be encouraged. 🍍

Another day another @bellefontainecemetery ! 🤗🌳🌲🌷🌸🪻🪦 I've lost count now but I think between IRL & virtual this may be my 7th or 8th. 🤔 It's clearly one of my favorite places in St. Louis. So beautiful. 😍
--
🌷💜
--
An arboretum is a botanical garden for trees. Bellefontaine is a level 3 arboretum meaning it has at least 500 species of woody plants, employs a collections curator, has substantial educational programming, collaborates with other arboreta, publicizes its collections, and actively participates in tree science and conservation. 🌳🤓
-- 
Sadie Waters (1869-1900) was born into a wealthy St. Louis family. She loved art and began studying it at an early age in Paris. Her work was exhibited in the Paris Salon from 1891 until her death. One notable painting, the La Vierge au Rosier, represents the Madonna and Child seated on a throne beneath an arch. Her grave features a bronze sculpture of a recumbent woman with the inscription "Ars Longa, Vita Brevis" which means Art is Long, Life Short. She is buried between her parents who were devastated by her early death. Some of her pieces are in storage at @museelouvre and are displayed when applicable.
-- 
A period after the last name on a marker meant that was the last male of that family line and there would be no heirs therefore the name would end with him. Period. (sorry, I had to say it, easy joke 😬😐🤷🏾)
-- 
When the city of St. Louis decided to stop allowing family and church burial grounds in the city in lieu of this huge garden cemetery, there was a mass exhumation and reinterment effort. This is the Presbyterian mass reinterment. Yes, about 500 folk's remains are in there. Apparently, their record-keeping sucked as Bellefontaine doesn't have a good way to say who is who. In contrast, the comparable Methodist mass reinterment situation up the walkway (not pictured) has immaculate records of who all were moved there. What a strange flex, but hey, I grew up Methodist so go us! 🎉🥳🤷🏾😐

✨ 47 ✨ 

I woke up this morning in a low mood. The night before, I'd thought about how many significant areas of my life had not panned out how I would have hoped. When you "keep living" as the old people encourage you to do, you encounter this new feeling of grief for the life you hoped you would have lived. This morning I intentionally journaled about gratitude to shift my point of view to what I have and not what I don't have.

"47 little years," as my mother would say ... yet I suspect that when she said this to me in my teens and twenties, she was the same age as I am now. 🤷🏾

Funny how life is.

We grow. We evolve. We mature. We transform. We expand. We unfold. We fill in all the nooks and crannies of our authentic selves. We shed the old. We adopt the new. 

And the waves never stop; they keep coming and often get bigger with every passing year. 🌊

I used to wait for the waves to calm down ... for the pace of life to give me some pause so I could *finally* get in there and live. That was for my twenties, lol.

Nowadays, I'm an avid surfer. 🏄🏾‍♀️ I run toward the waves of life and hop on top, riding gracefully until the shore, turning toward the sun to look for my next adventure.

Many things in these 47 years have been hard. And so many have been soft, gracious, beautiful, transforming, and good. 

✨ I press. ✨
✨ I turn, with great intention, toward the light. ✨

✨ I hope you do too. 🍍💛✨

Motherhood is a portal to the divine. ✨

It opens the door and gives us access to love, transformation, sacrifice, and hope. It is a path we take through anticipation, fear, exhaustion, fulfillment, joy, and unconditional love. 

It stretches us. ✨

It has stretched me. ✨

On this unexpected yet beautiful journey, I've been loved and loved in return. I have received and given divine strength, immeasurable selflessness, deep nurturing, and loving kindness. 

Motherhood has been an ongoing practice of surrender. ✨

"For decades, we’ve been told that positive thinking is the key to a happy, rich life. "F**k positivity," Mark Manson says. "Let’s be honest, shit is f**ked and we have to live with it." In his wildly popular Internet blog, Manson doesn’t sugarcoat or equivocate. He tells it like it is—a dose of raw, refreshing, honest truth that is sorely lacking today. The Subtle Art of Not Giving a F**k is his antidote to the coddling, let’s-all-feel-good mindset that has infected modern society and spoiled a generation, rewarding them with gold medals just for showing up.

Manson makes the argument, backed both by academic research and well-timed poop jokes, that improving our lives hinges not on our ability to turn lemons into lemonade, but on learning to stomach lemons better. Human beings are flawed and limited—"not everybody can be extraordinary, there are winners and losers in society, and some of it is not fair or your fault." Manson advises us to get to know our limitations and accept them. Once we embrace our fears, faults, and uncertainties, once we stop running and avoiding and start confronting painful truths, we can begin to find the courage, perseverance, honesty, responsibility, curiosity, and forgiveness we seek.

There are only so many things we can give a f**k about so we need to figure out which ones really matter, Manson makes clear. While money is nice, caring about what you do with your life is better, because true wealth is about experience. A much-needed grab-you-by-the-shoulders-and-look-you-in-the-eye moment of real-talk, filled with entertaining stories and profane, ruthless humor, The Subtle Art of Not Giving a F**k is a refreshing slap for a generation to help them lead contented, grounded lives."

Perfectionism is a fancy form of procrastination. 👩🏾‍🏫

"As a clinical psychologist, Dr. Nicole LePera often found herself frustrated by the limitations of traditional psychotherapy. Wanting more for her patients—and for herself—she began a journey to develop a united philosophy of mental, physical, and spiritual wellness that equips people with the interdisciplinary tools necessary to heal themselves. After experiencing the life-changing results herself, she began to share what she'd learned with others—and soon "The Holistic Psychologist" was born.

Now, Dr. LePera is ready to share her much-requested protocol with the world. In How to Do the Work, she offers both a manifesto for SelfHealing as well as an essential guide to creating a more vibrant, authentic, and joyful life. Drawing on the latest research from a diversity of scientific fields and healing modalities, Dr. LePera helps us recognize how adverse experiences and trauma in childhood live with us, resulting in whole body dysfunction—activating harmful stress responses that keep us stuck engaging in patterns of codependency, emotional immaturity, and trauma bonds. Unless addressed, these self-sabotaging behaviors can quickly become cyclical, leaving people feeling unhappy, unfulfilled, and unwell."

Just finished rereading The Alchemist: A Fable About Following Your Dreams by Paulo Coelho. I used to own a hardcopy of this book yet, when I pulled it up in Audible to listen I could not for the life of me remember reading it before. 🤔 But I know I did so; what in the world? 😐🤷🏽‍♀️ Anyhoo, it's a fable about a shepherd boy who wants to travel and ends up learning powerful lessons when he decides to follow his dream. It sounds simple; it's a quick read, yet it's chocked full of powerful lessons from which we can all benefit. I'm definitely keeping it on my "reread" list. It's in my Amazon Store if you're interested.  http://bit.ly/GlamaziniAmazonStore #linkinbio
. . .
"Combining magic, mysticism, wisdom and wonder into an inspiring tale of self-discovery, The Alchemist has become a modern classic, selling millions of copies around the world and transforming the lives of countless readers across generations.

Paulo Coelho's masterpiece tells the mystical story of Santiago, an Andalusian shepherd boy who yearns to travel in search of a worldly treasure. His quest will lead him to riches far different—and far more satisfying—than he ever imagined. Santiago's journey teaches us about the essential wisdom of listening to our hearts, of recognizing opportunity and learning to read the omens strewn along life's path, and, most importantly, to follow our dreams."

Just finished rereading Relational Intelligence: The People Skills You Need for the Life of Purpose You Want by Pastor Dharius Daniels . I read it a few years ago and promptly purchased the hard copy for my library. I think it should be essential reading for everyone in any relationship with another human, but *especially* for Christians, as I've observed a habit of believers operating in unhealthy relational dynamics and encouraging others to do so. The book used Jesus's relational framework to explain God's heart toward how we create, manage, assess, and experience healthy and divinely aligned relationships that are fruitful. I know that's what I want amen! 🍍🙌🏽 
.
Obviously, I'm keeping it on my "reread" list. It's in my Amazon Store if you're interested. http://bit.ly/GlamaziniAmazonStore 
.
🗨️ Comment 'GLAMAZINIREADS' and I'll DM you the link.
.
"Relational Intelligence is your action plan for getting smart about who you surround yourself with. Using Jesus's relational framework for choosing the twelve disciples, this book gives you the tools you need to define, discern, align, assess, and activate your relationships to unlock your greatest potential.
.
Years of ministry leadership experience have taught Dr. Dharius Daniels that there's no such thing as a casual relationship. All of our relationships either push us forward into our God-given purposes or hold us back from who we're meant to be. If you're serious about taking your life to the next level, you should be serious about taking your relationships to the next level, too.
.
Scripture gives us a blueprint for the way relationships should be managed, and this blueprint helps us construct and grow relationships that are fruitful. It tells us that our spiritual, physical, financial, emotional, and professional progress is greatly impacted by who we allow to be a part of our lives and what part we allow them to play. Relational Intelligence reminds us that with our destiny on the line, relationships are too consequential to nonchalantly roll the dice in managing them."
